# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boiler-feedwater-pump
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] An **air preheater** is any device designed to heat air before another process (for example, combustion in a boiler), with the primary objective of increasing the thermal efficiency of the process.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] They may be used alone or to replace a recuperative heat system or to replace a steam coil.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] In particular, this article describes the combustion air preheaters used in large boilers found in thermal power stations producing electric power from e.g. fossil fuels, biomass or waste.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The purpose of the air preheater is to recover the heat from the boiler flue gas which increases the thermal efficiency of the boiler by reducing the useful heat lost in the flue gas.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] As a consequence, the flue gases are also conveyed to the flue gas stack (or chimney) at a lower temperature, allowing simplified design of the conveyance system and the flue gas stack.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] It also allows control over the temperature of gases leaving the stack (to meet emissions regulations, for example).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] It is installed between the economizer and chimney.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] There are two types of air preheaters for use in steam generators in thermal power stations: One is a tubular type built into the boiler flue gas ducting, and the other is a regenerative air preheater.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] These may be arranged so the gas flows horizontally or vertically across the axis of rotation.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Another type of air preheater is the *regenerator* used in iron or glass manufacture.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Tubular preheaters consist of straight tube bundles which pass through the outlet ducting of the boiler and open at each end outside of the ducting.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Inside the ducting, the hot furnace gases pass around the preheater tubes, transferring heat from the exhaust gas to the air inside the preheater.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Ambient air is forced by a fan through ducting at one end of the preheater tubes and at other end the heated air from inside of the tubes emerges into another set of ducting, which carries it to the boiler furnace for combustion.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The tubular preheater ductings for cold and hot air require more space and structural supports than a rotating preheater design.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Further, due to dust-laden abrasive flue gases, the tubes outside the ducting wear out faster on the side facing the gas current.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Many advances have been made to eliminate this problem such as the use of ceramic and hardened steel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Many new circulating fluidized bed (CFB) and bubbling fluidized bed (BFB) steam generators are currently incorporating tubular air heaters offering an advantage with regards to the moving parts of a rotary type.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Dew point corrosion occurs for a variety of reasons.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The type of fuel used, its sulfur content and moisture content are contributing factors.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] However, by far the most significant factor in dew point corrosion is the metal temperature of the tubes.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] If the metal temperature within the tubes drops below the acid saturation temperature, usually at between 190 °F (88 °C) and 230 °F (110 °C), but sometimes at temperatures as high as 260 °F (127 °C), then the risk of dew point corrosion damage becomes considerable.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] There are two types of regenerative air preheaters: the rotating-plate regenerative air preheaters (RAPH) and the stationary-plate regenerative air preheaters (Rothemuhle).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The rotating-plate design (RAPH) consists of a central rotating-plate element installed within a casing that is divided into two (*bi-sector* type), three (*tri-sector* type) or four (*quad-sector* type) sectors containing seals around the element.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The seals allow the element to rotate through all the sectors, but keep gas leakage between sectors to a minimum while providing separate gas air and flue gas paths through each sector.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Tri-sector types are the most common in modern power generation facilities.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] In the tri-sector design, the largest sector (usually spanning about half the cross-section of the casing) is connected to the boiler hot gas outlet.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The hot exhaust gas flows over the central element, transferring some of its heat to the element, and is then ducted away for further treatment in dust collectors and other equipment before being expelled from the flue gas stack.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The second, smaller sector, is fed with ambient air by a fan, which passes over the heated element as it rotates into the sector, and is heated before being carried to the boiler furnace for combustion.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The third sector is the smallest one and it heats air which is routed into the pulverizers and used to carry the coal-air mixture to coal boiler burners.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Thus, the total air heated in the RAPH provides: heating air to remove the moisture from the pulverised coal dust, carrier air for transporting the pulverised coal to the boiler burners and the primary air for combustion.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The rotor itself is the medium of heat transfer in this system, and is usually composed of some form of steel and/or ceramic structure.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] It rotates quite slowly (around 1-2 RPM) to allow optimum heat transfer first from the hot exhaust gases to the element, then as it rotates, from the element to the cooler air in the other sectors.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] In this design the whole air preheater casing is supported on the boiler supporting structure itself with necessary expansion joints in the ducting.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The vertical rotor is supported on thrust bearings at the lower end and has an oil bath lubrication, cooled by water circulating in coils inside the oil bath.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] This arrangement is for cooling the lower end of the shaft, as this end of the vertical rotor is on the hot end of the ducting.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The top end of the rotor has a simple roller bearing to hold the shaft in a vertical position.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The rotor is built up on the vertical shaft with radial supports and cages for holding the baskets in position.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Radial and circumferential seal plates are also provided to avoid leakages of gases or air between the sectors or between the duct and the casing while in rotation.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] For on line cleaning of the deposits from the baskets steam jets are provided such that the blown out dust and ash are collected at the bottom ash hopper of the air preheater.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] This dust hopper is connected for emptying along with the main dust hoppers of the dust collectors.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The rotor is turned by an air driven motor and gearing, and is required to be started before starting the boiler and also to be kept in rotation for some time after the boiler is stopped, to avoid uneven expansion and contraction resulting in warping or cracking of the rotor.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The station air is generally totally dry (dry air is required for the instrumentation), so the air used to drive the rotor is injected with oil to lubricate the air motor.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Safety protected inspection windows are provided for viewing the preheater's internal operation under all operating conditions.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The baskets are in the sector housings provided on the rotor and are renewable.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The life of the baskets depend on the ash abrasiveness and corrosiveness of the boiler outlet gases.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The boiler flue gas contains many dust particles (due to high ash content) not contributing towards combustion, such as silica, which cause abrasive wear of the baskets, and may also contain corrosive gases depending on the composition of the fuel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] For example, Indian coals generally result in high levels of ash and silica in the flue gas.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The wear of the baskets therefore is generally more than other, cleaner-burning fuels.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] In this RAPH, the dust laden, corrosive boiler gases have to pass between the elements of air preheater baskets.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The elements are made up of zig zag corrugated plates pressed into a steel basket giving sufficient annular space in between for the gas to pass through.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] These plates are corrugated to give more surface area for the heat to be absorbed and also to give it the rigidity for stacking them into the baskets.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Hence frequent replacements are called for and new baskets are always kept ready.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] In the early days, Cor-ten steel was being used for the elements.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Today due to technological advance many manufacturers may use their own patents.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Some manufacturers supply different materials for the use of the elements to lengthen the life of the baskets.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] In certain cases the unburnt deposits may occur on the air preheater elements causing it to catch fire during normal operations of the boiler, giving rise to explosions inside the air preheater.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Sometimes mild explosions may be detected in the control room by variations in the inlet and outlet temperatures of the combustion air.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The heating plate elements in this type of regenerative air preheater are also installed in a casing, but the heating plate elements are stationary rather than rotating.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Instead the air ducts in the preheater are rotated so as to alternatively expose sections of the heating plate elements to the upflowing cool air.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] As indicated in the adjacent drawing, there are rotating inlet air ducts at the bottom of the stationary plates similar to the rotating outlet air ducts at the top of the stationary plates.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] Stationary-plate regenerative air preheaters are also known as Rothemuhle preheaters, manufactured for over 25 years by Balke-Dürr GmbH of Ratingen, Germany.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] A regenerator consists of a brick checkerwork: bricks laid with spaces equivalent to a brick's width between them, so that air can flow relatively easily through the checkerwork.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The idea is that as hot exhaust gases flow through the checkerwork, they give up heat to the bricks.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] The airflow is then reversed, so that the hot bricks heat up the incoming combustion air and fuel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] For a glass-melting furnace, a regenerator sits on either side of the furnace, often forming an integral whole.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] For a blast furnace, the regenerators (commonly called **Cowper stoves**) sit separate to the furnace.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] A furnace needs no less than two stoves, but may have three.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/air-preheater] One of the stoves is 'on gas', receiving hot gases from the furnace top and heating the checkerwork inside, whilst the other is 'on blast', receiving cold air from the blowers, heating it and passing it to the blast furnace.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A **high pressure watertube boiler** (also spelled *water-tube* and *water tube*) is a type of boiler in which water circulates in tubes heated externally by fire.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Fuel is burned inside the furnace, creating hot gas which boils water in the steam-generating tubes.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In smaller boilers, additional generating tubes are separate in the furnace, while larger utility boilers rely on the water-filled tubes that make up the walls of the furnace to generate steam.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The heated water/steam mixture then rises into the steam drum.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Here, saturated steam is drawn off the top of the drum.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In some services, the steam passes through tubes in the hot gas path (a superheater) to become superheated.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Superheated steam is a dry gas and therefore is typically used to drive turbines, since water droplets can severely damage turbine blades.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Saturated water at the bottom of the steam drum returns to the lower drum via large-bore 'downcomer tubes', where it pre-heats the feedwater supply.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] (In large utility boilers, the feedwater is supplied to the steam drum and the downcomers supply water to the bottom of the waterwalls).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] To increase economy of the boiler, exhaust gases are also used to pre-heat combustion air blown into the burners, and to warm the feedwater supply in an economizer.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Such watertube boilers in thermal power stations are also called *steam generating units*.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The older fire-tube boiler design, in which the water surrounds the heat source and gases from combustion pass through tubes within the water space, is typically a much weaker structure and is rarely used for pressures above 2.4 MPa (350 psi).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A significant advantage of the watertube boiler is that there is less chance of a catastrophic failure: there is not a large volume of water in the boiler nor are there large mechanical elements subject to failure.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A water-tube boiler was patented by Blakey of England in 1766 and was made by Dallery of France in 1780.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "The ability of watertube boilers to be designed without the use of excessively large and thick-walled pressure vessels makes these boilers particularly attractive in applications that require dry, high-pressure, high-energy steam, including steam turbine power generation".
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Besides, they are frequently employed in power generation plants where large quantities of steam (ranging up to 500 kg/s) having high pressures i.e. approximately 16 megapascals (160 bar) and high temperatures reaching up to 550 °C are generally required.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] For example, the Ivanpah solar-power station uses two Rentech Type-D watertube boilers for plant warmup, and when operating as a fossil-fueled power station.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Modern boilers for power generation are almost entirely water-tube designs, owing to their ability to operate at higher pressures.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Where process steam is required for heating or as a chemical component, then there is still a small niche for fire-tube boilers.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One notable exception is in typical nuclear-power stations (Pressurized Water Reactors), where the steam generators are generally configured similar to firetube boiler designs.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In these applications the hot gas path through the "Firetubes" actually carries the very hot/high pressure primary coolant from the reactor, and steam is generated on the external surface of the tubes.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Their ability to work at higher pressures has led to marine boilers being almost entirely watertube.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This change began around 1900, and traced the adoption of turbines for propulsion rather than reciprocating (i.e. piston) engines – although watertube boilers were also used with reciprocating engines, and firetube boilers were also used in many marine turbine applications.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There has been no significant adoption of water-tube boilers for railway locomotives.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A handful of experimental designs were produced, but none of them were successful or led to their widespread use.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most water-tube railway locomotives, especially in Europe, used the Schmidt system.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most were compounds, and a few uniflows.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Norfolk and Western Railway's *Jawn Henry* was an exception, because it used a steam turbine combined with an electric transmission.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Not successful and re-boilered with a conventional boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A slightly more successful adoption was the use of hybrid water-tube/fire-tube systems.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] As the hottest part of a locomotive boiler is the firebox, it was an effective design to use water-tubes here and a conventional fire-tube boiler as an economiser (i.e. pre-heater) in the usual position.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One famous example of this was the USA Baldwin 4-10-2 No.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Built as a compound with a boiler pressure of 2,400 kilopascals (350 psi) it successfully covered over 160,000 kilometres (100,000 mi) in service.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] After a year however, it became clear that any improvements were overwhelmed by the extra costs, and it was retired as a museum display at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A series of twelve experimental locomotives were constructed at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's Mt.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Clare shops under the supervision of George H.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Emerson, but none of them were replicated in any numbers.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The only water-tube locomotive boiler used in any large numbers was the Brotan boiler, invented by Johann Brotan in Austria in 1902 and found sparsely throughout Europe, although Hungary had around 1,000 in service.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Like the Baldwin 60000, it combined a water-tube firebox with a fire-tube barrel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Brotan's original characteristic was a long steam drum running *above* the main barrel, resembling a Flaman boiler in appearance.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] While traction engines were usually built with locomotive boiler as its frame, other types of steam road vehicles such as lorries and cars used a wide range of different boiler types.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Road transport pioneers Goldsworthy Gurney and Walter Hancock both used water-tube boilers in their steam carriages around 1830.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most undertype wagons used water-tube boilers.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many manufacturers used variants of the vertical cross-tube boiler, including Atkinson, Clayton, Garrett and Sentinel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Other types include the Clarkson 'thimble tube' and the Foden O-type wagon's pistol-shaped boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Steam fire-engine makers such as Merryweather usually used water-tube boilers for their rapid steam-raising capacity.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many steam cars used water-tube boilers, and the Bolsover Express company even made a water-tube replacement for the Stanley Steamer fire-tube boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The 'D-type' is the most common type of small- to medium-sized boilers, similar to the one shown in the schematic diagram.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It is used in both stationary and marine applications.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It consists of a large steam drum vertically connected to a smaller water drum (a.k.a.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "mud drum") via multiple steam-generating tubes.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These drums and tubes as well as the oil-fired burner are enclosed by water-walls - additional water-filled tubes spaced close together so as to prevent gas flow between them.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These water wall tubes are connected to both the steam and water drums, so that they act as a combination of preheaters and downcomers as well as decreasing heat loss to the boiler shell.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The M-type boilers were used in many US World War II warships including hundreds of *Fletcher*-class destroyers.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Three sets of tubes form the shape of an M, and create a separately fired superheater that allows better superheat temperature control.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In addition to the mud drum shown on a D-type boiler, an M-type has a water-screen header and a waterwall header at the bottom of the two additional rows of vertical tubes and downcomers.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The *low water content* boiler has a lower and upper header connected by watertubes that are directly impinged upon from the burner.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This is a "furnace-less" boiler that can generate steam and react quickly to changes in load.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Designed by the American firm of Babcock & Wilcox, this type has a single drum, with feedwater drawn from the bottom of the drum into a header that supplies inclined water-tubes.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The watertubes supply steam back into the top of the drum.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Furnaces are located below the tubes and drum.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This type of boiler was used by the Royal Navy's *Leander*-class frigates and in United States Navy New Orleans-class cruisers.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Stirling boiler has near-vertical, almost-straight watertubes that zig-zag between a number of steam and water drums.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Usually there are three banks of tubes in a "four drum" layout, but certain applications use variations designed with a different number of drums and banks.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] They are mainly used as stationary boilers, owing to their large size, although the large grate area does also encourage their ability to burn a wide range of fuels.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Originally coal-fired in power stations, they also became widespread in industries that produced combustible waste and required process steam.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Paper pulp mills could burn waste bark, sugar refineries their bagasse waste.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Named after its designers, the then Poplar-based Yarrow Shipbuilders, this type of three-drum boiler has three drums in a delta formation connected by watertubes.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The drums are linked by straight watertubes, allowing easy tube-cleaning.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This does, however, mean that the tubes enter the drums at varying angles, a more difficult joint to caulk.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Outside the firebox, a pair of cold-leg pipes between each drum act as downcomers.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Due to its three drums, the Yarrow boiler has a greater water capacity.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Hence, this type is usually used in older marine boiler applications.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Its compact size made it attractive for use in transportable power generation units during World War II.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In order to make it transportable, the boiler and its auxiliary equipment (fuel oil heating, pumping units, fans etc.), turbines, and condensers were mounted on wagons to be transported by rail.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The White-Forster type is similar to the Yarrow, but with tubes that are gradually curved.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This makes their entry into the drums perpendicular, thus simpler to make a reliable seal.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Thornycroft & Company, the Thornycroft type features a single steam drum with two sets of watertubes either side of the furnace.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These tubes, especially the central set, have sharp curves.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Apart from obvious difficulties in cleaning them, this may also give rise to bending forces as the tubes warm up, tending to pull them loose from the tubeplate and creating a leak.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There are two furnaces, venting into a common exhaust, giving the boiler a wide base tapering profile.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In a forced circulation boiler, a pump is added to speed up the flow of water through the tubes.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] After about 1910, the **Baker valve gear** was the main competitor to Walschaerts valve gear for steam locomotives in the United States.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] Strictly speaking it was not a valve gear but a variable expansion mechanism adapted to the Walschaerts layout replacing the expansion link and sliding die block.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The Baker arrangement used more pivot bearings or *pin joints*, but avoided the die slip inherent to the expansion link, with the aim of lessening wear and the need for service; it could also facilitate longer valve travel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] In the early 1900s there were many efforts to create a new valve gear to replace the by-then-standard Walschaerts valve gear.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] In the United States the Young, Southern, Caprotti and Franklin patterns were used on a few classes, but only the Baker pattern won more than limited acceptance.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] Baker Company, of Swanton, Ohio; a builder of steam traction engines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The idea came from an employee called Gifford but was developed by the Baker company with the first patents being issued in 1903 and with patents issued through at least November, 1912.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The Baker Locomotive Valve Gear was produced by the Pilliod Co. of Swanton, Ohio.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] Subsequent versions were produced up to the end of steam service.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] It was particularly popular on the Norfolk and Western Railway, and almost all later N&W engines used it.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] Other extensive users included the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Nickel Plate Road, the New York Central Railroad and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] There was always debate about the advantages of Baker gear, the main criticism being the number of pin joints and possible lost motion.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] While popular with railroads on the east, western states tended to continue with the Walschaerts pattern.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] In Britain, Baker gear was popular amongst model engineers but in full-size practice the length of the yoke and the width of the assembly may have been difficult to accommodate within the restricted loading gauge.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] Other locomotives to use Baker valve gear were the New Zealand Railways J class, Ja class, Jb class, some Ka class, and the South Australian Railways 620 class.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The Baker valve gear replaces the expansion link of the Walschaerts gear with an assembly of levers and links which produces the same effect of allowing continuous variation valve travel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The remainder of the gear is the same, so that the return crank and combination lever take the same form, although the proportions are usually modified.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The Pilliod Co. sold the gear as a single assembly which was mounted on the frame in the location ordinarily occupied by the Walschaerts expansion link.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The parts were arranged so that when the yoke was centered, the connection of the main link to the bellcrank was in a line with the two pivots on the yoke.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] At this point, the back and forth motion of the lower end of the main link left the top relatively motionless as main link swung back and forth on the swing links.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] In forward motion, the yoke was pushed forward, so that its upper pivot was in front of the bell crank-main link connection.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] Moving the eccentric arm back and forth lowered and raised the top of the main link.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] This motion was translated by the bellcrank into back and forth motion of the radius rod.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/baker-valve-gear] The angle of the yoke controlled the relative motion, and therefore the cutoff; tilting the yoke backwards reversed the motion of the radius rod.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] A **bash valve** is a valve within a piston engine, used to control the admission of the working fluid.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] They are directly actuated valves, operated by contact between the piston and the valve tip.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Bash valves have the advantage of great simplicity, for manufacture and operation.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Their disadvantages are that their opening and closing times are relatively crudely controlled, compared to other types of valve gear.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The valve is usually constructed as a circular poppet valve with a conical seat, inserted into the cylinder from the outside.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] A protrusion on the inside is hit by the piston as it approaches top dead centre, forcing the valve open.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Bash valves are usually held closed by the pressure of fluid in the reservoir behind them.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] There may be a light spring to assist closing when the reservoir is empty.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] For this reason they are used as inlet valves, not exhaust.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] An exhaust bash valve would have the cylinder pressure and the piston actuation both acting to open it, with nothing to close it.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Bash valves are not widely used in steam engines, although they are known.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Most examples were applied to some form of uniflow steam engine; unlike the more common slide and piston-valved engines with their bidirectional-flow ports, uniflow engines use inlet ports at the cylinder ends and an exhaust near the centre.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Although the opening time of a bash valve is fixed, imprecisely controlled and always occurs near top dead centre, this is not a major drawback for a steam engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] A more important requirement is the ability to accurately control the closing time of the valve, and for its duration to be adjustable in order to 'drive' the engine, according to varying load.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Some designs of uniflow engine have used a combined mechanical and electromagnetic valve to do this.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The valve is opened mechanically, then held by an electromagnet.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] This requires less electrical power to merely hold the valve than to open it.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] A patent for such an engine was granted to Sturtevant in 1968.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The same idea has recently been revived as the main feature of an Advanced Uniflow Steam Engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] In this engine, a second valve is used for exhaust purposes in the later part of the cycle too, although this one is bashed shut, rather than opened.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Bash valves have also been used for the *ad hoc* conversion of commonplace petrol small engines, such as lawnmowers, into hobbyist steam engines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The original petrol engine sparkplug mounting hole is used as the location for a new piston-actuated bash valve, together with the original exhaust valve.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Performance and efficiency are not a need of such projects.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] One successful application for bash valves has been to pneumatic motors.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Owing to the characteristics of compressed air pneumatic power, their simplicity is valuable and their inefficiencies with other fluids are less important.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Compressed air is supplied cold to the motor.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Energy is represented solely by the pressure of the air not, unlike steam, by the combination of pressure and temperature.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Efficient operation of a steam engine relies upon expansion of the steam during the piston stroke, which relies upon accurate valve timing and an early closure of the valve.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] During the expansion phase of the steam it does not expand in a simple isothermal fashion, but does so adiabatically, much of the energy having been supplied as heat rather than pressure.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The compressed air motor is thermodynamically simpler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] This means that expansion is less important, valve timings are thus longer and less crucial and so a simple valve may be adequate.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] To provide long opening times, the bash valve normally incorporates some form of tappet mechanism.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Rather than a valve that is held open by the piston directly, the valve becomes double-acting and is opened by the piston's impact at one end of the stroke and closed by a further impact at the other end of the stroke.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The tappet and valve are commonly separate, allowing the valve to remain in a well-defined fully open position throughout the stroke, however the tappet is bounced around by the piston.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Where a reciprocating action is produced, such as for a rock drill, the valve may be actuated either by inertia of the frame or by the movement of the working piston.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] As the piston hammers back and forth, it impacts a small tappet, which in turn moves the air valve and so reverses the flow of air to the piston.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] One form of this, the arc tappet valve, was an important feature of the Ingersoll rock drill, the first successful compressed air rock drill for use in mining and tunneling.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] This used a valve that rotated in a slight arc, rather than sliding.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The valve was double-acting, controlling the air supply for both the power and the return stroke.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The innovation that made this valve so reliable, thus successful, was a separate tappet that was actuated by the piston in passing at the middle of the stroke, rather than being hammered by a jarring direct impact of the piston.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The mid-stroke actuation also opened the valve passageways earlier, before top dead centre, allowing in air that provided a cushioning effect.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] This further improved the action of the drill, giving a powerful stroke on the working piston and drill rod, but with less damaging hammering to the frame of the drill.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Bash valves are not used in such engines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The cylinder peak pressures of an Otto cycle engine are too high for such a valve to remain on its seat.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Bash valves are also used in a 'single-shot' situation, where a valve is opened once and then remains open until the contents of a pressure vessel are released.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] Such valves are used in some fire extinguishers and pre-charged air rifles.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] These valves are arranged so that once lifted off their seat, pressure underneath the valve becomes sufficient to keep the valve raised and so it remains open until the pressure reservoir is empty.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/bash-valve] The valve is then closed by a light spring.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] A **beam engine** is a type of steam engine where a pivoted overhead beam is used to apply the force from a vertical piston to a vertical connecting rod.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] This configuration, with the engine directly driving a pump, was first used by Thomas Newcomen around 1705 to remove water from mines in Cornwall.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The efficiency of the engines was improved by engineers including James Watt, who added a separate condenser; Jonathan Hornblower and Arthur Woolf, who compounded the cylinders; and William McNaught, who devised a method of compounding an existing engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Beam engines were first used to pump water out of mines or into canals but could be used to pump water to supplement the flow for a waterwheel powering a mill.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The **rotative beam engine** is a later design of beam engine where the connecting rod drives a flywheel by means of a crank (or, historically, by means of a sun and planet gear).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] These beam engines could be used to directly power the line-shafting in a mill.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] They also could be used to power steam ships.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The first beam engines were water-powered and used to pump water from mines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] A preserved example may be seen at the Straitsteps Lead Mine in Wanlockhead in Scotland.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Beam engines were extensively used to power pumps on the English canal system when it was expanded by means of locks early in the Industrial Revolution, and also to drain water from mines in the same period, and as winding engines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The first steam-related beam engine was developed by Thomas Newcomen.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] This was not, strictly speaking, steam powered, as the steam introduced below the piston was condensed to create a partial vacuum thus allowing atmospheric pressure to push down the piston.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] It was therefore called an Atmospheric Engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The Newcomen atmospheric engine was adopted by many mines in Cornwall and elsewhere, but it was relatively inefficient and consumed a large quantity of fuel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The engine was improved by John Smeaton but James Watt resolved the main inefficiencies of the Newcomen engine in his Watt steam engine by the addition of a separate condenser, thus allowing the cylinder to remain hot.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Technically this was still an atmospheric engine until (under subsequent patents) he enclosed the upper part of the cylinder, introducing steam to also push the piston down.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] This made it a true steam engine and arguably confirms him as the inventor of the steam engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] He also patented the centrifugal governor and the parallel motion. the latter allowed the replacement of chains round an arch head and thus allowed its use as a rotative engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] His patents remained in place until the start of the 19th Century and some say that this held back development.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] However, in reality development had been ongoing by others and at the end of the patent period there was an explosion of new ideas and improvements.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Watt's beam engines were used commercially in much larger numbers and many continued to run for 100 years or more.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Watt held patents on key aspects of his engine's design, but his rotative engine was equally restricted by James Pickard's patent of the simple crank.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The beam engine went on to be considerably improved and enlarged in the tin- and copper-rich areas of south west England, which enabled the draining of the deep mines that existed there.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Consequently, the Cornish beam engines became world-famous, as they remain among the most massive beam engines ever constructed.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Because of the number of patents on various parts of the engines and the consequences of patent infringements, examples exist of Beam Engines with no makers name on any of the parts (Hollycombe Steam Collection).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] In a rotative beam engine, the piston is mounted vertically, and the piston rod drives the beam as before.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] A connecting rod from the other end of the beam, rather than driving a pump rod, now drives a flywheel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Early Watt engines used Watt's patent sun and planet gear, rather than a simple crank, as use of the latter was protected by a patent owned by James Pickard.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Once the patent had expired, the simple crank was employed universally.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Once rotary motion had been achieved a drive belt could be attached beside the flywheel.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] This transmitted the power to other drive shafts and from these other belts could then be attached to power a variety of static machinery e.g. threshing, grinding or milling machines.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The first steam-powered ships used variants of the rotative beam engine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] These marine steam engines – known as side-lever, grasshopper, crosshead, or 'walking beam', among others – all varied from the original land-based machines by locating the beam or beams in different positions to take up less room on board ship.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Compounding involves two or more cylinders; low-pressure steam from the first, high-pressure, cylinder is passed to the second cylinder where it expands further and provides more drive.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] This is the compound effect; the waste steam from this can produce further work if it is then passed into a condenser in the normal way.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The first experiment with compounding was conducted by Jonathan Hornblower, who took out a patent in 1781.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] His first engine was installed at Tincroft Mine, Cornwall.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] It had two cylinders – one 21-inch (0.53 m) diameter with 6-foot (1.8 m) stroke and one 27-inch (0.69 m) diameter with 8-foot (2.4 m) stroke – placed alongside each other at one end of the beam.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The early engines showed little performance gain: the steam pressure was too low, interconnecting pipes were of small diameter and the condenser ineffective.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] At this time the laws of thermodynamics were not adequately understood, particularly the concept of absolute zero.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Engineers such as Arthur Woolf were trying to tackle an engineering problem with an imperfect understanding of the physics.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] In particular, their valve gear was cutting-in at the wrong position in the stroke, not allowing for expansive working in the cylinder.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] Successful Woolf compound engines were produced in 1814, for the Wheal Abraham copper mine and the Wheal Vor tin mine.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] William McNaught patented a compound beam engine in 1845.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] On a beam engine of the standard Boulton & Watt design he placed a high-pressure cylinder, on the opposite side of the beam to the existing single cylinder, where the water pump was normally fitted.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] This had two important effects: it massively reduced the pressure on the beam, and the connecting steam pipe, being long, acted as an expansive receiver – the element missing in the Woolf design.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] This modification could be made retrospectively, and engines so modified were said to be "McNaughted".
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/beam-engine] The advantages of a compound engine were not significant at pressures under 60 pounds per square inch (410 kPa), but showed at over 100 psi (690 kPa).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] A **boiler feedwater pump** is a specific type of pump used to pump feedwater into a steam boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] The water may be freshly supplied or returning condensate produced as a result of the condensation of the steam produced by the boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] These pumps are normally high pressure units that take suction from a condensate return system and can be of the centrifugal pump type or positive displacement type.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] Feedwater pumps range in size up to many kilowatts and the electric motor is usually separated from the pump body by some form of mechanical coupling.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] Large industrial condensate pumps may also serve as the feedwater pump.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] In either case, to force the water into the boiler, the pump must generate sufficient pressure to overcome the steam pressure developed by the boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] This is usually accomplished through the use of a centrifugal pump.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] Another common form of feedwater pump runs constantly and is provided with a minimum flow device to stop overpressuring the pump on low flows.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] The minimum flow usually returns to the tank or deaerator.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] Mechanical seals of boiler feedwater pumps often show signs of electrical corrosion.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] The relative movement between the sliding ring and the stationary ring provokes static charging which is not diverted due to the very low conductivity of the boiler water (below one micro-Siemens per cm [μS/cm]).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] Within short periods of operation – in some cases, only a few hundred operational hours – pieces having the size of fingertips break off from the sliding and/or the stationary ring and cause rapid increases in leakage current.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] Diamond-coated (DLC) mechanical seals avoid this problem and extend durability remarkably.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] Steam locomotives and the steam engines used on ships and stationary applications such as power plants also require feedwater pumps.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] In this situation, though, the pump was often powered using a small steam engine that ran using the steam produced by the boiler.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] A means had to be provided, of course, to put the initial charge of water into the boiler (before steam power was available to operate the steam-powered feedwater pump).
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] The pump was often a positive displacement pump that had steam valves and cylinders at one end and feedwater cylinders at the other end; no crankshaft was required.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] A duplex steam pump has two sets of steam and water cylinders.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] They are not physically connected but the steam valves on the first pump are operated by the movement of the second pump's piston rod, and vice versa.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] The result is that there are no "dead spots" and the pump is always self-starting.
[src:boiler-feedwater-pump/boiler-feedwater-pump] An injector pump uses the Venturi effect and steam condensation to deliver water to a boiler.
